text=:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a:Essential: {Category.MorphosyntacticDiversity$:essential}%0a:Title: Repetition Clefts%0a:Author: Thomas_H_K%0a:Section: B%0a:Completed: 10.04.2021 - 15:13%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210421-181111-257220#%0a* [-21.04.2021 - 11:11-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210421-181111-257220#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aWhat I wrote is I wrote this%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aA repetition cleft is a sentence structure that places emphasis on information some information in a sentence. It is an extension of the -, which is a more accepted structure.%0a %0aA pseudo-cleft (or ‘Wh’ cleft) is a complex sentence, formed by splitting a sentence into two clauses. Then, we insert some form of ‘be’ in the middle, typically ‘is’ or ‘was.’ Then, we insert a question word at the beginning of the sentence (What, Why, Where, When, How). It is used to put emphasis on the missing information from the first part of the sentence.%0a%0aExample of pseudo-cleft: “I crave chocolate.” can be turned into the pseudo-cleft “What I crave is chocolate.” %0a%0aTo make a pseudocleft into a repetition cleft, we replace the non-question clause with the original sentence. In practice, this looks somewhat like a syntactical reduplication. Typically, repetition clefts allowing reversing the clauses of the cleft, and some beginnings are more acceptable when used in reverse forms.%0a%0aExamples:%0a"I crave chocolate” becomes “What I crave is I crave chocolate"%0a"I need it now!” becomes “When I need it is I need it now!"%0a%0a"Where the car is is the car is in the lake."%0a"James should be working on it is who should be working on it." (Example of reversal)%0a"We should do it my way is how we should do it." (Example of reversal)%0a%0aRepetition clefts occur more frequently in speech than in writing. They typically called ‘marginal,’ meaning they are somewhere between strictly grammatical and ungrammatical. Interestingly, they do not correlate with any demographical features but are widespread in several different dialects.%0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://www.researchgate.net/publication/268001311_The_Frozenness_of_Pseudoclefts_-_Towards_an_Inequality-based_Syntax%0ahttps://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/repetition-clefts%0ahttps://www.grammaring.com/pseudo-cleft-sentences%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
