%0a%3c %0a%3c "Where the car is is the car is in the lake."%0a%3c "James should be working on it is who should be working on it." (Example of reversal)%0a%3c "We should do it my way is how we should do it." (Example of reversal)%0a%3c %0a%3c Repetition clefts occur more frequently in speech than in writing. They typically called ‘marginal,’ meaning they are somewhere between strictly grammatical and ungrammatical. Interestingly, they do not correlate with any demographical features but are widespread in several different dialects.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c https://www.researchgate.net/publication/268001311_The_Frozenness_of_Pseudoclefts_-_Towards_an_Inequality-based_Syntax%0a%3c https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/repetition-clefts%0a%3c https://www.grammaring.com/pseudo-cleft-sentences%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
